<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="510" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" reason="1">Discussion.</emphasis>
The general outline and profile of the specimens from Spitsbergen are similar to those of specimens figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnova, T. N." box="[398,582,188,213]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" pagination="39 - 49" refId="ref18461" refString="Smirnova, T. N. (1987) New taxa of late Volgian and early Hauterivian brachiopods of the Russian platform. Paleontological Journal, 21 (1), 39 - 49." type="journal article" year="1987">Smirnova (1987</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 4, figs. 1–2) from the Russian Platform, in particular that in pl. 4, fig. 1. This specimen appears to be smooth, developing costae at the anterior margin. The Russian Platform specimens reach maximum lengths close to 
<quantity box="[531,598,260,285]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnova, T. N." box="[614,792,260,285]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" pagination="39 - 49" refId="ref18461" refString="Smirnova, T. N. (1987) New taxa of late Volgian and early Hauterivian brachiopods of the Russian platform. Paleontological Journal, 21 (1), 39 - 49." type="journal article" year="1987">Smirnova 1987</bibRefCitation>
, p. 42) so are smaller than the Spitsbergen material that reach 
<quantity box="[218,283,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
in length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">
Smirnova provided serial sections of 
<specimenCount box="[637,808,332,357]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smirnova. It" authorityYear="1987" box="[853,1155,332,357]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Norellidae" genus="Pseudomonticlarella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="varia">
<emphasis box="[853,1155,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Pseudomonticlarella varia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1987, fig. 1a–b). Both series of sections show a septalium and crura that arch ventrally anteriorly. These are features that are shared with the Spitsbergen specimen (
<figureCitation box="[458,530,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1704,1726]" captionTargetBox="[162,1434,188,1692]" captionTargetId="figure-173@8.[149,1434,184,1692]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Transverse serial sections of Pseudomonticlarella varia Smirnova, seep 13, PMO 227.416. Sections 0.4–1.1 mm given at higher magnification below dotted black line. Serial sections prepared perpendicular to maximum length of the specimen, numbering of sections starts at 0.0 mm the initial section through the specimen. Dimensions of sectioned specimen: L 7.0+; W 8.1; T 4.1 mm (+ = dimension damaged/specimen broken in that direction). Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4951758" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4951758/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). The internal structures (from the initial section through the brachiopod) were traced for 
<quantity box="[268,368,439,464]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.12" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" unit="mm" value="4.12">4.12 mm</quantity>
in specimen No. 139/584 (
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnova, T. N." box="[676,853,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" pagination="39 - 49" refId="ref18461" refString="Smirnova, T. N. (1987) New taxa of late Volgian and early Hauterivian brachiopods of the Russian platform. Paleontological Journal, 21 (1), 39 - 49." type="journal article" year="1987">Smirnova 1987</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 1a) and for 
<quantity box="[1044,1144,439,464]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" unit="mm" value="1.45">1.45 mm</quantity>
in specimen No. 139/590 (fig. 1b). In the Spitsbergen specimen the internal structures were traced to section 
<quantity box="[1093,1179,476,501]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
(i.e., 
<quantity box="[1245,1332,476,501]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
from the initial section through the specimen).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">
It was thought originally that these diminutive specimens could be juveniles of the form referred herein to 
<taxonomicName authority="Sandy &amp; Hryniewicz &amp; Hammer &amp; Nakrem &amp; Little, 2014" authorityName="Sandy &amp; Hryniewicz &amp; Hammer &amp; Nakrem &amp; Little" authorityYear="2014" box="[151,438,583,608]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Rhynchonellidae" genus="Ptilorhynchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="mclachlani" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,438,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Ptilorhynchia mclachlani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[445,537,583,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[445,537,583,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
However, posteriorly the ventral valve of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smirnova. It" authorityYear="1987" box="[1021,1321,583,608]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Norellidae" genus="Pseudomonticlarella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="varia">
<emphasis box="[1021,1321,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Pseudomonticlarella varia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks any developing or incipient costae, which are often present posteriorly on specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sandy &amp; Hryniewicz &amp; Hammer &amp; Nakrem &amp; Little" authorityYear="2014" box="[1140,1428,620,645]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Rhynchonellidae" genus="Ptilorhynchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="mclachlani">
<emphasis box="[1140,1428,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Ptilorhynchia mclachlani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Also, posteriorly, the dorsal valve of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smirnova. It" authorityYear="1987" box="[587,889,655,680]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Norellidae" genus="Pseudomonticlarella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="varia">
<emphasis box="[587,889,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Pseudomonticlarella varia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is weakly sulcate (possibly enhanced by some decortication). This sulcate condition does not appear to characterize specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sandy &amp; Hryniewicz &amp; Hammer &amp; Nakrem &amp; Little" authorityYear="2014" box="[1109,1396,692,717]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Rhynchonellidae" genus="Ptilorhynchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="mclachlani">
<emphasis box="[1109,1396,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Ptilorhynchia mclachlani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sandy &amp; Hryniewicz &amp; Hammer &amp; Nakrem &amp; Little" authorityYear="2014" box="[257,543,727,752]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Rhynchonellidae" genus="Ptilorhynchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="mclachlani">
<emphasis box="[257,543,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Ptilorhynchia mclachlani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smirnova. It" authorityYear="1987" box="[598,897,727,752]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Norellidae" genus="Pseudomonticlarella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="varia">
<emphasis box="[598,897,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Pseudomonticlarella varia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not co-occuring. Obviously they should cooccur if they are conspecific (although this could reflect a collecting failure). The specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smirnova. It" authorityYear="1987" box="[151,459,799,824]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Norellidae" genus="Pseudomonticlarella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="varia">
<emphasis box="[151,459,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Pseudomonticlarella varia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
all occur with similar maximum dimensions and there are currently no other intermediate-sized forms between these and larger-sized species such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sandy &amp; Hryniewicz &amp; Hammer &amp; Nakrem &amp; Little" authorityYear="2014" box="[964,1249,836,861]" class="Rhynchonellata" family="Rhynchonellidae" genus="Ptilorhynchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchonellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" phylum="Brachiopoda" rank="species" species="mclachlani">
<emphasis box="[964,1249,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Ptilorhynchia mclachlani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis box="[199,712,871,896]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,705,871,896]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510">Stratigraphic and geographic distribution</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Upper Volgian–Lower (?Upper) Ryazanian of Spitsbergen and originally described from the Upper Volgian of the Russian Platform (
<bibRefCitation author="Smirnova, T. N." box="[934,1112,908,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="510" pagination="39 - 49" refId="ref18461" refString="Smirnova, T. N. (1987) New taxa of late Volgian and early Hauterivian brachiopods of the Russian platform. Paleontological Journal, 21 (1), 39 - 49." type="journal article" year="1987">Smirnova 1987</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
